                    <msContents n="1">
                        <!--increment n attribute for ms containing multiple ms items-->
                        <summary>A fragment of the <title xml:lang="san">Cāndravyākaraṇa</title> of
                            the Buddhist grammarian <name type="person" role="oth" key="local_00141 VIAF_46773592">
                        <persName xml:lang="san" type="standard">Candragomin</persName>
                     </name> with its most
                            widespread and best known commentary, the <title xml:lang="san" type="general">Cāndravyākaraṇavṛtti</title>, for a long time
                            believed to be the work of Candragomin himself, but now generally
                            attributed to an author called <name type="person" role="aut" key="local_00331 VIAF_">
                        <persName xml:lang="san" type="standard">Dharmadāsa</persName>
                     </name>, of
                            which nothing else is known (Dash 1986; Oberlies 1989). In this manuscript each <term xml:lang="san">sūtra</term> (i.e. rule) is separated from the
                            commentary to the previous <term xml:lang="san">sūtra</term> by a double
                                <term xml:lang="san">daṇḍa</term> followed by a small blank and
                            another double <term xml:lang="san">daṇḍa</term>, thus facilitating
                            their identification despite the poor condition of the folios. The
                            fragment contains a portion of the first section (<term xml:lang="san">pāda</term>, literally “quarter”) of the fifth chapter (<term xml:lang="san">adhyāya</term>), starting at some place before rule
                            5.1.16, <term xml:lang="san">śenṅitoḥ</term>, which is legible, though
                            barely, on <locus from="1r" to="1r">f. 1r4</locus>, followed by rules
                            17, <term xml:lang="san">jyāvraścapracchabhrasjāṃ</term>, <locus from="1r" to="1r">f. 1r4</locus>; 18, <term xml:lang="san">vaśas
                                tiṅśity apiti</term>, <locus from="1r" to="1r">f. 1r5</locus>; and
                            19, <term xml:lang="san">vyaco ñṇityasi</term>, <locus from="1v" to="1v">f. 1v6</locus>. The first rule identified by Bendall (1883: 159),
                            namely 5.1.21, <term xml:lang="san">liṭy aśver dvirukte</term>, appears
                            on <locus from="1v" to="1v">f. 1v1</locus>. In the rest of the
                            manuscript the following <term xml:lang="san">sūtra</term>s are legible,
                            more or less clearly: 23, <term xml:lang="san">svapaḥ</term>, <locus from="1v" to="1v">1v4</locus>; 24, <term xml:lang="san">caṅi</term>,
                                <locus from="1v" to="1v">1v4</locus>; 25, <term xml:lang="san">yaṅi</term>, <locus from="1v" to="1v">1v5</locus>; 26, <term xml:lang="san">vyesyamoḥ</term>, <locus from="1v" to="1v">1v5</locus>; 27, <term xml:lang="san">cāyaḥ kīḥ</term>, <locus from="1v" to="1v">1v5]</locus>; 28, <term xml:lang="san">pres styaś
                                ca tatavatoḥ</term>, <locus from="1v" to="1v">1v6</locus>; 29, <term xml:lang="san">sprśadravamūrtyoḥ śyaḥ</term>, <locus from="1v" to="1v">1v6</locus>; 30, <term xml:lang="san">prateḥ</term>, <locus from="1v" to="1v">1v7</locus>; 34, <term xml:lang="san">pyāyaḥ
                                pīḥ</term>, <locus from="2r" to="2r">2r3</locus>; 36, <term xml:lang="san">liḍyaṅoḥ</term>, <locus from="2r" to="2r">2r5</locus>; 37, <term xml:lang="san">vā śveḥ</term>, <locus from="2r" to="2r">2r5</locus>; 39, <term xml:lang="san">hvaḥ</term>, <locus from="2v" to="2v">2v1</locus>; 40, <term xml:lang="san">dvitve</term>, <locus from="2v" to="2v">2v2</locus>; 41, <term xml:lang="san">na tasmin</term>, <locus from="2v" to="2v">2v3</locus>; 42, <term xml:lang="san">liṭi</term>, <locus from="2v" to="2v">2v4</locus>; 43, <term xml:lang="san">vayo yaḥ</term>,
                                <locus from="2v" to="2v">2v5</locus>; 44, <term xml:lang="san">ver
                                apiti vā</term>, <locus from="2v" to="2v">2v6</locus>; 45, <term xml:lang="san">lyapi ca</term>, <locus from="2v" to="2v">2v6</locus>; 46, <term xml:lang="san">jyaḥ</term>, <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r1</locus>; 47, <term xml:lang="san">vyaḥ</term>, <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r1</locus>; 48, <term xml:lang="san">parer
                                vā</term>, <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r2</locus>; 49, <term xml:lang="san">eco śity āt_</term>, <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r2</locus>; 50, <term xml:lang="san">aliṭi¦ vyaḥ</term>, <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r4-3r5</locus>; 51, <term xml:lang="san">sphurisphulor ghañi</term>, <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r5</locus>;
                            52, <term xml:lang="san">dīṅo</term>
                            <sic>
                        <term xml:lang="san">’kṅitsan</term>
                     </sic>
                            <term xml:lang="san">lyapi</term>, <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r6</locus>;
                            53, <term xml:lang="san">mimyor akhalaci</term>, <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r7</locus>; 54, <term xml:lang="san">liyo vā</term>, <locus from="3v" to="3v">3v1</locus>; 55, <term xml:lang="san">apaguro
                                ṇamuli</term>, <locus from="3v" to="3v">3v3</locus>; 56, <term xml:lang="san">
                        <damage type="broken">-1-</damage>sphuror ṇau</term>,
                                <locus from="3v" to="3v">3v4</locus>; 57, <term xml:lang="san">prajane viyaḥ</term>, <locus from="3v" to="3v">3v4</locus>; 58,
                                <term xml:lang="san">bhiyaḥ</term>
                            <sic>
                        <term xml:lang="san">prajojakāt_</term>
                     </sic>, <locus from="3v" to="3v">3v5</locus>; 59, <term xml:lang="san">smeś ca</term>, <locus from="3v" to="3v">3v6</locus>; 60, <sic>
                        <term xml:lang="san">krīṅjīnā</term>
                     </sic>, <locus from="3v" to="3v">3v7</locus>;
                            61, <sic>
                        <term xml:lang="san">aṣṭivuṣvaskādeḥ ṣas saḥ</term>
                     </sic>,
                                <locus from="4r" to="4r">4r2</locus>; 62, <term xml:lang="san">ṇo
                                naḥ</term>, <locus from="4r" to="4r">4r4</locus>; 63, <term xml:lang="san">yo vali lopaḥ</term>, <locus from="4r" to="4r">4r5</locus>; (<term>sūtra</term> 64, <term xml:lang="san">ver
                                anacaḥ</term> is omitted, certainly due to a scribal mistake, as the
                            commentary on rule 63 is incomplete but, after a <term xml:lang="san">daṇḍa</term>, the text continues with the final part of the
                            commentary on <term>sūtra</term> 64); 65, <term xml:lang="san">halas
                                tipsipaḥ</term>, <locus from="4r" to="4r">4r6</locus>; 66, <term xml:lang="san">soḥ</term>, <locus from="4r" to="4r">4r7</locus>; 67,
                                <term xml:lang="san">ṅyāpo dirghāt</term>, <locus from="4r" to="4r">4r7</locus>; 68, <term xml:lang="san">eṅ hrasvāt sambuddhāv
                                ataḥ</term>, <locus from="4r" to="4r">4r8</locus>; 69, <term xml:lang="san">hrasvasyātiṅi piti tuk</term>, <locus from="4v" to="4v">4v2</locus>; 70, <sic>
                        <term xml:lang="san">phe</term>
                     </sic>,
                                <locus from="4v" to="4v">4v4</locus>; 71, <term xml:lang="san">āṅmāṅah</term>, <locus from="4v" to="4v">4v4</locus>; 72, <term xml:lang="san">dīrghasya</term>, <locus from="4v" to="4v">4r5</locus>; 73, <term xml:lang="san">padāntasya vā</term>, <locus from="4v" to="4v">4v5</locus>; 74, <term xml:lang="san">iko yaṇ
                                aci</term>, <locus from="4v" to="4v">4v6</locus>; 75, <term xml:lang="san">
                        <unclear reason="damaged">eco
                                ’yavāyāvaḥ</unclear>
                     </term>, <locus from="4v" to="4v">4v7</locus>.
                            The last legible sutra is 5.1.76, <term xml:lang="san">yi pare
                                ’vāvau</term> on <locus from="4v" to="4v">f. 4v7</locus>. The rest
                            of the chapter, which comprises 142 <term xml:lang="san">sūtra</term>s,
                            is lost. The manuscript is badly damaged, but the readable portions
                            correspond quite closely to the printed edition of the
                                <title>Cāndravyākaraṇavṛtti</title> (Chatterji 1965). </summary>
                       
